		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ventureburn.com/?p=200485</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Axoft just raised a $55 million Series A investment, which will help the company move forward with the research needed to make its biomimetic implantable Brain Computer Interfaces (iBCIs) a</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/axoft-raises-55m-to-transform-brain-machine-tech/" data-wpel-link="internal">Axoft Raises $55M to Transform Brain-Machine Tech</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://axoft.us/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Axoft </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">just raised a $55 million Series A </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/earlybird-vc-raises-e360m-for-new-european-tech-funds/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">investment</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">, which will help the company move forward with the research needed to make its biomimetic implantable Brain Computer Interfaces (iBCIs) a reality. This is happening at a time when the world is getting closer to a future where neurological disabilities can be overcome with a constant, problem-free electronic intervention.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The just-closed funding round to back Axoft was led by C.P. Group Innovation, with an impressive lineup consisting of its investments Alumni Ventures, the Stanford President&#8217;s Venture Fund, Hillhouse Investment and Gaorong Ventures. It has now raised more than $60 million in all since it was founded in 2021.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Solving the &#8220;Rigid&#8221; Problem</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">While companies like Neuralink and Blackrock Neurotech have dominated headlines, the field has long struggled with a fundamental biological hurdle: the human brain is soft, while traditional electronics are rigid. Standard implants often trigger the body’s immune response, leading to tissue scarring (gliosis) and &#8220;signal drift&#8221; as the implant moves within the skull.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Axoft’s solution lies in its proprietary material, Fleuron&#x2122;. Developed from research at Harvard University, Fleuron is roughly 10,000 times softer than the materials used in current brain implants. </span></p>
<div id="attachment_200486" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-200486" class="wp-image-200486 size-large" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/axoft-1536x945-1-1024x630.jpg" alt="axoft logo" width="1024" height="630" /><p id="caption-attachment-200486" class="wp-caption-text">Source: axoft</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This extreme flexibility allows the device to mimic the mechanical properties of brain tissue, virtually eliminating scarring and enabling the sensors to stay in close, stable contact with neurons for years rather than months.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;At Axoft, we believe that better neural signals are the foundation of everything else that is built on,&#8221; said Dr Paul Le Floch, co-founder and CEO of Axoft. &#8220;By unlocking a higher quality of data without damaging the brain, we open the door to real-time AI decoding and treatments for conditions that were previously considered unreachable.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News: </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/earlybird-vc-raises-e360m-for-new-european-tech-funds/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">Earlybird VC Raises €360M for New European Tech Funds</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Global Clinical Momentum</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The Series A represents Axoft moving from a clinical-stage company that was extremely research-heavy to one that has already completed first-in-human clinical trials on 11 patients across the world, including recording sessions in Mass General Brigham and The Panama Clinic.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">In a rare move reflecting the international competition for neurotech advancements, it was also revealed that Axoft has recently tested its soft neural probes in Shanghai, China.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Scaling for the Future</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Axoft plans to use the $55 million to execute a three-pronged growth strategy:</span></p>
<ol>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>Regulatory Approval:</b><span style="font-weight: 400"> Aggressively seeking U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) milestones for its iBCI platform.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>Manufacturing Expansion:</b><span style="font-weight: 400"> Establish a GMP facility in the Boston area. This will enable Axoft to manufacture its implants on a large scale and also commercialise the Fleuron material for other medical applications, including &#8220;organ-on-a-chip&#8221; devices.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400"><b>Global Clinical Trials: </b><span style="font-weight: 400">Conducting more extensive international clinical trials in deeper brain regions than previously undertaken, aimed at investigating complex issues such as tumour mapping, stroke rehabilitation, and consciousness disorders.</span></li>
</ol>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Considering neurological disorders currently afflict 1 in 3 worldwide users, the stress to consistently deliver a safe and reliable interface has never been greater. Axoft&#8217;s gentle methodology may be the critical leap required to bring state-of-the-art brain-machine communication to the forefront of modern medicine.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/axoft-raises-55m-to-transform-brain-machine-tech/" data-wpel-link="internal">Axoft Raises $55M to Transform Brain-Machine Tech</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
